  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "19. And he saith unto them, Follow me—rather, as the same expression is rendered in Mark, \"Come ye after Me\" (Mr 1:17).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and I will make you fishers of men—raising them from a lower to a higher fishing, as David was from a lower to a higher feeding (Ps 78:70-72).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Here was their call to the office of apostles. It is observable that God’s calls of men to places of dignity and honour, and his appearances of favour to them, have ordinarily been when they have been busied in the honest employments of their callings. Saul was seeking his father’s asses, David keeping his father’s sheep, when the Lord called them to the kingdom. The shepherds were feeding their flocks when they had the revelation of Christ. He calleth four apostles from their fishery; Amos from amongst the herdmen of Tekoa; Matthew from the receipt of custom; Moses when keeping Jethro’s flock, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Exodus 3:1,2",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Exodus 3:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ",2",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Gideon from the threshing floor, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Judges 6:11",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Judges 6:11",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". God never encourages idleness, but despiseth not persons in meanest employments. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Follow me, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that is, to return no more to your employment. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "I will make you fishers of men:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " here is the work of ministers set out, to gain souls to God; they are not to fish merely for a livelihood, much less for honour and applause to themselves, but to win souls to God, and are to bait their hooks and order their nets to this end, which they will never serve, if either by general discourses they make the meshes so wide that all will dart through them, or if by their wit and learning they make their discourses so fine and curious that few or none of their hearers can understand them. Nor will all our art make us fishers of men: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I will make you, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " saith Christ. Paul may plant, and Apollos may water, God must give the increase. But yet we must order our nets rationally and probably in order to our end, and without that cannot expect God’s blessings. Nor were the apostles presently to enter upon the work of the ministry, but first to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "follow",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " him. And indeed such should all gospel ministers be. In the choice of Matthias, Peter limited the people in their election to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "those that had accompanied with them all the time the Lord Jesus went in and out amongst them, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bldvs",
        "text": " Acts 1:21",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 1:21",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Other ministers commonly prove fishers for something else, not for the souls of men. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And he saith unto them, follow me,.... These two brethren had been the disciples of John, as Theophylact thinks, and which seems agreeable to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 1:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and though through John's pointing out Christ unto them, they had some knowledge of him, and conversation with him, yet they abode with him but for that day, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 1:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and afterwards returned to their master; and upon his imprisonment, betook themselves to their former employment: from whence Christ now calls them to be his disciples, saying \"follow me\", or \"come after me\": that is, be a disciple of mine; see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 14:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". And to encourage them to it, makes use of this argument; \"and\", or \"for\", I \"will make you fishers of men\": you shall be fishers still, but in a higher sense; and in a far more noble employment, and to much better purpose. The net they were to spread and cast was the Gospel, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 13:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for Christ made them not , \"fishers of the law\", to use the words of Maimonides (g), but fishers of the Gospel. The sea into which they were to cast the net was first Judea, and then the whole world; the fish they were to catch were the souls of men, both among Jews and Gentiles; of whose conversion and faith they were to be the happy instruments: now none could make them fishers in this sense, or fit them for such service, and succeed them in it, but Christ; and who here promises it unto them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(g) Hilcot. Talmud. Torah, c. 1. sect. 12. so Dr. Lightfoot cites the phrase, but in Ed. Amsterd. it is , \"the judgments of the law\". ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(g) Hilcot. Talmud. Torah, c. 1. sect. 12. so Dr. Lightfoot cites the phrase, but in Ed. Amsterd. it is , \"the judgments of the law\". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
